Bill Clinton
On January 21, 1998, the extra-marital relationship Bill
Clinton, the 42nd President of the United States, had with Monica
Lewinsky, a former White House intern, was reported in press.
President Clinton denied allegations of a sexual relationship
and of suborning perjury. On July 17, President Clinton served
with grand jury subpoena, later withdrawn in return for testimony.
On July 28, Immunity/Cooperation Agreement was reached between
Monica Lewinsky and Office of Independent Counsel.
On August 17, President Clinton testified before the grand
jury. Later he publicly acknowledged improper relationship with
Lewinsky.
On September 9, Office of Independent Counsel submitted
Referral to Congress, accusing President Clinton of perjury and
obstruction of justice in the Monica Lewinsky Affair.
On September 11, the U.S. House of Representatives voted to
release the prosecutor's report.
On October 5, the U.S. House of Representatives Judiciary
Committee began a debate on whether to launch a formal impeachment
inquiry against President Clinton.
On November 19, the Judiciary Committee began impeachment
hearings against Clinton.
On December 8 and 9, the White House lawyers presented their
defense of Clinton.
On December 11, Clinton apologized to the country for his
conduct with Lewinsky and said he would accept a congressional
censure or rebuke.
On December 11-12, the Judiciary Committee passed all the four
impeachment articles against Clinton.
The U.S. House of Representatives held a meeting on December 19
to cast votes on the four articles of impeachment. The House
approved two of the four impeachment articles, formally
rcommnending that Clinton be tried in the Sanete for committing perjury
before a federal grand jury and obstructing justice. The lawmakers
rejected two other articles acccusing Clinton of perjury in the
Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit and abuse of presidential
power. Clinton would only be removed from office if two- thirds of
senators voted to convict him.  
